To this effect were her expotulations, joyning her angelical face to the diabolical countenance of the Moor, which he bedew'd with her tears. I am apt to imagine that who ever had een uch a Viion, would have taken it for an Angel embracing a Devil. As for our Don Pedro, he began to think his fair Elvira as ugly as her Negro, who at lat cating his eyes on his importunate Mitres, whom he had not till then vouchaf'd a look, and with his craggy hand removing her face from his own, aid to her, with a hollow voice;
What would


you have of me, Madam, and why will you not let me die in quiet? Do you not think it enough that you have reduc'd me to the condition I am in? or do you expect I hould, at the point of death, acrifice the few minutes I have left, to the atisfaction of your inatiable inclinations? Take a Husband, Madam, take a Husband, and expect no more from me. I hall not ee you any more, nor tate of what you have brought me; all my buines now is onely to die, ince I am not good for any thing but the grave.

But not unwilling to make a full dicovery of himelf;
This conformity of Adventures, aid he to Don Pedro, very much heightned the mutual love we had for one another, though it till kept us both within the limits of civility and our duty, when ever our paion would have advis'd us to prefer our atisfaction before the engagements wherein we were involv'd upon the account of our Families. Hitherto had my love had the ucces I could have wih'd my elf, I mean, o as not to obtain the final reward of it, which he put off till after the arrival of her Husband, that is, when the cloak of Marriage might cover all the inconveniences likely to enue upon an appointment which uppoes omewhat more then a private converation. I hall not tell you any thing of the beauty of Virginia, but onely that it is impoible to ay too much of it, and that I could ay as much of it as would haply puzzle your faith to believe. I hall forbear, till you have een her, and her Couin Violanta, who lives with her, which when you have, it will haply force an acknowledgment


from you, that Spain can hardly afford any thing fairer than thee two incomparable Couins, and, when you come to dicoure with them, that you never met with any Women more witty.

In the mean time, his Lacquey kindled a little Char-coal fire; for in Spain there's but little other Fuel; but for that, all Countries mut be content with what proviion Nature hath been pleas'd to make them; though he be ever o much a Stepmother, there's no repining at her dipoal of things. He alo laid clean heets, or hould have done if he had any, on his Mater's bed, who, having bidden the Lady good-night, left her in poeion of his Chamber, double-locking the door upon her, and went to Bed, I know not upon what pretence, to a Gentleman of his acquaintance that had a Chamber


in the ame Houe. He lept in all likelihood better in his Friend's, than the Lady he had recommended to his own Bed did in his; he never drew bit, till the cries about the Streets awoke him; he ceas'd not weeping and bewailing her elf all night long. Don Garcias got up, rubb'd and powder'd, and made himelf as pruce and as youthful as he could. Being come to his own Chamber-door, he lay'd his Ear to the Key-hole, and having heard the poor Lady till bemoaning her elf, he made no difficulty to go in to her. His preence heightened the violence of her affliction, and not able to look on him with any command of her grief;
You ee, aid he to him, a woman, who was, no longer ince than yeterday, the mot eteem'd of any in Vailladolid, but at preent the mot depicable, and mot infamous, and in a condition now much more likely to raie compaion, than he hath ometime been to caue envy. But how great oever the mifortune may be whereto I am reduc'd, the eaonable kindnes I receiv'd from you, may yet in ome meaure remedy it, if after you have afforded me the Sanctuary of your Chamber till night, you get me convey'd thence, either in a Sedan or Coach, to a Convent which I hall name to you. But may I, added he, after all the Obligations you have cat on me, entreat you to be at the trouble to go to my Houe, to enquire what is aid and done there; and, in fine, to inform your elf, what dicoure there is about the Court and City, concerning the unhappy Woman, whom you have o generouly taken into your protection.

The inviible Lady uffer'd him to go on in his dicoure, out of an expectation, that, among the many things he aid, he might let fall omewhat, which might contribute to the further dicovery he was deirous to make of him. But at lat finding nothing to faten on but his ditrut of her, he made him this Reply;
Well, Don Carlos, have you been ufficiently cenorious, or am I yet to tell you, that your aurance of my incerity, mut be the iue of your own belief of it, and that your hatines will rather retard than haten the accomplihment of your deires. Aure your elf therefore, without any further reflections on the grounds you have to upect me, that I am very real and incere, and that you hall find me no les in all that hall happen between us, and I expect you hould be the like to me. That were but jut, replies Don Carlos, but it were requiite I hould ee you, and know who you


are. It hall not be long ere you do, replies the Lady, and therefore, in the mean time, receive this Antidote againt impatience, that onely by the trial I hall make of your contancy, you may attain what you pretend to from me, who now aure you, (to the end your courthip may not be without ome encouragement and hope of requital) that I am equal to you as to Quality; that I have an Etate plentiful enough to maintain you in as much plendour as the greatet Prince in the Kingdom; that I am young; that I may challenge omewhat of beauty; and for matter of wit, you are better tor'd your elf, then to be doubtful whether I have any or not.
